{"title_page": "Immunogenetics", "text_new": "{{For|the journal|Immunogenetics (journal)}}\n{{unreferenced|date=August 2014}}\n\n'''Immunogenetics''' or '''immungenetics''' is the branch of [[medical genetics]] that explores the relationship between the [[immune system]] and [[genetics]].\n\nAutoimmune diseases, such as type 1 diabetes, are complex genetic traits which result from defects in the immune system. Identification of genes defining the immune defects may identify new target genes for therapeutic approaches. Alternatively, genetic variations can also help to define the immunological pathway leading to disease.\n\n==Origin==\nIts origin is usually attributed to [[Edward Jenner]], who discovered in 1796 that [[cowpox]], or vaccinia, induced protection against human [[smallpox]].\nIt took two centuries before the [[World Health Organization]] announced in 1979 that smallpox had been [[eradication of smallpox|eradicated]].\n\nThe term immunogenetics is based on the two words [[immunology]] and [[genetics]], and is defined as \"a sub discipline of genetics which deals with the genetic basis of the immune response (immunity)\" according to MeSH.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/68007125|title=Immunogenetics - MeSH - NCBI|website=www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nGenetics (based on Greek \u03b3\u03b5\u03bd\u03b5\u03ac ''gene\u00e1'' \"descent\" and \u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 ''g\u00e9nesis'' \"origin\")<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/genetic|title=genetic {{!}} Origin and meaning of genetic by Online Etymology Dictionary|website=www.etymonline.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> is the science researching the transfer of characteristics from one generation to the next. The genes of an organism (strands of DNA) and the transfer of genes from the parent to the child generation of an organism in the scope of possible variations are the basis of genetics.\n\nImmunology deals with the biological and biochemical basis for the body's defense against germs (such as [[bacteria]], [[virus]]es, and [[Mycosis|fungi]]), as well as against foreign agents such as biological toxins and environmental pollutants, and failures and malfunctions of these defense mechanisms. Apart from these external effects on the organism, there are also defense reactions regarding the body's own cells, e.g. in the scope of the bodily reactions on cancer and the lacking reaction of a body on healthy cells in the scope of an immune-mediated disease. Hence, immunology is a sub-category of [[biology]].\n\nThe term immunogenetics comprises all processes of an organism, which are, on the one hand, controlled and influenced by the genes of the organism, and are, on the other hand, significant with regard to the immunological defense reactions of the organism.\n\n==History==\n\nThe medical history of [[immunology]] and the [[immune system]] dates back to the 19th century. However, the prevention and early defense of diseases was an essential task for all shamans, medicine men and early \"doctors\" during the entire human evolution. The first Nobel Prize in the field of immunogenetics was awarded to [[Baruj Benacerraf]], [[Jean Dausset]] and [[George Davis Snell]] in 1980 for discovering genetically determined cellular surface structures, which control immunological reactions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1980/summary/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 1980|website=NobelPrize.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Current research fields==\nSince 1972,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/ashi_history|title=ASHI History - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> numerous H&I (histocompatibility and immunogenetics) organizations have been founded specializing in research activities on a large number of different questions in immunogenetics. Both the acceleration of and the decreasing costs for the sequencing of the genes have resulted in a more intensive research of both academic and commercial working groups. Current research topics particularly deal with forecasts on the course of diseases and therapy recommendations due to genetic dispositions and how these dispositions can be affected by agents (gene therapy).\n\nA special focus is often laid on the forecast regarding and therapy of genetically based [[autoimmune disease]]s, which include all diseases caused by an extreme reaction of the immune system against the body's own tissue. By mistake, the immune system recognizes the body's own tissue as a foreign object which is to be fought. This can result in serious inflammatory reactions which may permanently damage the respective organs. Autoimmune diseases, the outbreak and/or course of which can be visible in the individual genome of the organism, include [[multiple sclerosis]], [[diabetes type I]], [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and [[Crohn's disease]]. As for multiple sclerosis, an article in the journal ''Nature'' dated May 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4016/19108.01|title=Neil Miller on \u201cGenome, epigenome and RNA sequences of monozygotic twins discordant for multiple sclerosis\u201d|date=2010-07-06|website=SciVee|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> showed that this autoimmune disease is not caused by a genetic variation but the course and the treatability are considerably influenced by genetic dispositions. This research was based on analyzing three monovular pairs of twins, of which one twin has contracted multiple sclerosis whereas the other one has not.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Histocompatibility]]\n* [[Human Immunology#American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics]]\n* [[European Federation for Immunogenetics]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110210192027/http://www.ebi.ac.uk/imgt/ IMGT Databases at the European Bioinformatics Institute]\n* [http://www.womenshealth.gov/faq/autoimmune-diseases.cfm FAQ on autoimmune diseases by US Department for Health and Human Services]\n* [http://www.genome.gov/20019523 Homepage of the National Genome association studies]\n\n{{Genetics |expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Medical genetics]]\n[[Category:Branches of immunology]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the journal|Immunogenetics (journal)}}\n{{unreferenced|date=August 2014}}\n\n'''Immunogenetics''' or '''immungenetics''' is the branch of [[medical genetics]] that explores the relationship between the [[immune system]] and [[genetics]].\n\nAutoimmune diseases, such as type 1 diabetes, are complex genetic traits which result from defects in the immune system. Identification of genes defining the immune defects may identify new target genes for therapeutic approaches. Alternatively, genetic variations can also help to define the immunological pathway leading to disease.\n\n==Origin==\nIts origin is usually attributed to [[Edward Jenner]], who discovered in 1796 that [[cowpox]], or vaccinia, induced protection against human [[smallpox]].\nIt took two centuries before the [[World Health Organization]] announced in 1979 that smallpox had been [[eradication of smallpox|eradicated]].\n\nThe term immunogenetics is based on the two words [[immunology]] and [[genetics]], and is defined as \"a sub discipline of genetics which deals with the genetic basis of the immune response (immunity)\" according to MeSH.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/68007125|title=Immunogenetics - MeSH - NCBI|website=www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nGenetics (based on Greek \u03b3\u03b5\u03bd\u03b5\u03ac ''gene\u00e1'' \"descent\" and \u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 ''g\u00e9nesis'' \"origin\")<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/genetic|title=genetic {{!}} Origin and meaning of genetic by Online Etymology Dictionary|website=www.etymonline.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> is the science researching the transfer of characteristics from one generation to the next. The genes of an organism (strands of DNA) and the transfer of genes from the parent to the child generation of an organism in the scope of possible variations are the basis of genetics.\n\nImmunology deals with the biological and biochemical basis for the body's defense against germs (such as [[bacteria]], [[virus]]es, and [[Mycosis|fungi]]), as well as against foreign agents such as biological toxins and environmental pollutants, and failures and malfunctions of these defense mechanisms. Apart from these external effects on the organism, there are also defense reactions regarding the body's own cells, e.g. in the scope of the bodily reactions on cancer and the lacking reaction of a body on healthy cells in the scope of an immune-mediated disease. Hence, immunology is a sub-category of [[biology]].\n\nThe term immunogenetics comprises all processes of an organism, which are, on the one hand, controlled and influenced by the genes of the organism, and are, on the other hand, significant with regard to the immunological defense reactions of the organism.\n\n==History==\n\nThe medical history of [[immunology]] and the [[immune system]] dates back to the 19th century. However, the prevention and early defense of diseases was an essential task for all shamans, medicine men and early \"doctors\" during the entire human evolution. The first Nobel Prize in the field of immunogenetics was awarded to [[Baruj Benacerraf]], [[Jean Dausset]] and [[George Davis Snell]] in 1980 for discovering genetically determined cellular surface structures, which control immunological reactions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1980/summary/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 1980|website=NobelPrize.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Current research fields==\nSince 1972,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ashi-hla.org/page/ashi_history|title=ASHI History - American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|website=www.ashi-hla.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> numerous H&I (histocompatibility and immunogenetics) organizations have be founded specializing in research activities on a large number of different questions in immunogenetics. Both the acceleration of and the decreasing costs for the sequencing of the genes have resulted in a more intensive research of both academic and commercial working groups. Current research topics particularly deal with forecasts on the course of diseases and therapy recommendations due to genetic dispositions and how these dispositions can be affected by agents (gene therapy).\n\nA special focus is often laid on the forecast regarding and therapy of genetically based [[autoimmune disease]]s, which include all diseases caused by an extreme reaction of the immune system against the body's own tissue. By mistake, the immune system recognizes the body's own tissue as a foreign object which is to be fought. This can result in serious inflammatory reactions which may permanently damage the respective organs. Autoimmune diseases, the outbreak and/or course of which can be visible in the individual genome of the organism, include [[multiple sclerosis]], [[diabetes type I]], [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and [[Crohn's disease]]. As for multiple sclerosis, an article in the journal ''Nature'' dated May 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4016/19108.01|title=Neil Miller on \u201cGenome, epigenome and RNA sequences of monozygotic twins discordant for multiple sclerosis\u201d|date=2010-07-06|website=SciVee|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> showed that this autoimmune disease is not caused by a genetic variation but the course and the treatability are considerably influenced by genetic dispositions. This research was based on analyzing three monovular pairs of twins, of which one twin has contracted multiple sclerosis whereas the other one has not.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Histocompatibility]]\n* [[Human Immunology#American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics|American Society for Histocompatibility and Immunogenetics]]\n* [[European Federation for Immunogenetics]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110210192027/http://www.ebi.ac.uk/imgt/ IMGT Databases at the European Bioinformatics Institute]\n* [http://www.womenshealth.gov/faq/autoimmune-diseases.cfm FAQ on autoimmune diseases by US Department for Health and Human Services]\n* [http://www.genome.gov/20019523 Homepage of the National Genome association studies]\n\n{{Genetics |expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Medical genetics]]\n[[Category:Branches of immunology]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immunogenetics"}
{"title_page": "Christoph Crois\u00e9", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n'''Christoph Raphael Friedwart Crois\u00e9''' (born 3 December 1993 in [[Filderstadt]]/[[Germany]] but raised in [[Niederlenz]]/[[Switzerland]]) is a French-German-Swiss cellist.\n\n== Biography and Career ==\n[[File:Christoph Crois\u00e9 w\u00e4hrend einer CD Aufnahme, Kirche Oberstrass, Z\u00fcrich, November 2017.jpg|thumb|250x250px|Christoph Crois\u00e9 during a CD recording, Church Oberstrass, Zurich/Switzerland, November 2017]]Christoph Crois\u00e9 had his first Cello lessons at the age of seven with Katharina K\u00fchne. Since 2007, so at the age of 14, he was taught and guided by Alexander Neustroev, a Solo-Cellist at [[Tonhalle, Z\u00fcrich|Zurich's Tonhalle]]. When he turned 20 he moved to Berlin to study with Wolfgang-Emanuel Schmidt at [[Universit\u00e4t der K\u00fcnste|Berlin University of Arts]].\n\nAlso from the age of 14 he started attending various master classes and has since benefitted from the advice of [[Steven Isserlis]], [[Michael Sanderling]], [[David Geringas]], Walter Grimmer, and [[Frans Helmerson]].\n\nAt the age of 17, Christoph made his debut at [[Carnegie Hall]] in [[New York City]] after having won the IBLA Foundation Grand Prize,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Concerts in New-York |url=http://www.musicalolympus.ru/en/projects-in-the-world/archive/443-new-york |website=Musical Olympus |accessdate=20 October 2018|title=New-York }}</ref> which included a concert tour through the United States.\n\nHis debut album with Oxana Shevchenko was released in May 2015 on Quartz Classics.<ref>{{Citation|title={{lrm}}\"Visions\" von Christoph Crois\u00e9 & Oxana Shevchenko|date=2015-05-10|url=https://itunes.apple.com/ch/album/visions/994069142|language=de-CH|access-date=2018-10-10}}</ref> His second album \"Summer Night\", including [[Othmar Schoeck]]'s cello concerto, was released in February 2018 on GENUIN classics.<ref>{{Citation|title={{lrm}}\"Schoeck: Summer Night\" von Christoph Crois\u00e9, Gevorg Gharabekyan & I Tempi|date=2018-02-02|url=https://itunes.apple.com/ch/album/schoeck-summer-night/1336109953|language=de-CH|access-date=2018-10-10}}</ref> His third album (Haydn, Vivaldi Cello Concertos) was released in March 2019 on AVIE Records<ref>{{Citation|title={{lrm}}\"Haydn, Vivaldi Cello Concertos\" von Christoph Crois\u00e9, Eurasian Soloists Chamber Orchestra & Sherniyaz Mussakhan|url=https://itunes.apple.com/de/album/haydn-vivaldi-cello-concertos/1453080565|language=de-de|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref> and won the Supersonic Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pizzicato.lu/frisch-und-unbedingt-horenswert-haydns-cellokonzerte-mit-christoph-croise/|title=Frisch und unbedingt h\u00f6renswert: Haydns Cellokonzerte mit Christoph Crois\u00e9|date=2019-04-15|website=Pizzicato|language=fr-FR|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref> from the [[Pizzicato (magazine)|Pizzicato]] Magazine and the \u201eClef D\u2019Or\u201c for the best concerto album of 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://t58aa7439.emailsys2a.net/mailing/134/2430765/3705578/8537/b18324da48/index.html|title=Les Clefs d'Or ResMusica 2019|website=t58aa7439.emailsys2a.net|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref> from the [[:fr:ResMusica|ResMusica]] Magazine.  His fourth CD \"The Russian Album\" was released on November 1st 2019 on AVIE Records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.avie-records.com/releases/the-russian-album/|title=The Russian Album|website=Avie Records|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n== Performances ==\nAs a soloist, he has appeared under the batons of conductors including [[Michael Sanderling|M. Sanderling]], [[Mario Venzago|M. Venzago]], [[Douglas Boyd|D. Boyd]], L. Gendre, [[:de:Kevin_Griffiths|K. Griffiths]], [[:lb:David_Reiland|D. Reiland]], A. Guliyev, A. Ardal, M. Dones and D. Botinis, with various orchestras including the [[Orchester Musikkollegium Winterthur|Musikkollegium Winterthur]], the St. Petersburg Symphony Orchestra, the [[Bern Symphony Orchestra]], the State Symphony Orchestra [[Baku]]/Azerbaijan, the Camerata Zurich, the [[Munich Radio Orchestra]], the Camerata Switzerland,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://joachim-raff.ch/jra-eroeffnungskonzert/ |title = JRA-Er\u00f6ffnungskonzert \u2013 Joachim-Raff-Gesellschaft}}</ref> the [[Southwest German Philharmonic Orchestra of Constance]], the State Symphony Orchestra, St. Petersburg, the [[Collegium Musicum Basel]], the [[Orchestre symphonique de Mulhouse]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://issuu.com/media.pop/docs/prog_orchestre_symphonique_de_mulho_21bcb6dd054790 |title = Programme de l'Orchestre Symphonique de Mulhouse, Saison 2016 2017}}</ref> the [[Radio Symphony Orchestra]], Tirana, the [[:fr:Sinfonietta_de_Lausanne|Sinfonietta de Lausanne]], the [[Sichuan Symphony Orchestra]], the [[Saint Petersburg Academic Symphony Orchestra]], the Bavarian Philharmonic Chamber Orchestra, the [[Izmir State Symphony Orchestra]], the Orquesta Sinfonica de Michoacan, the Harbin Symphony Orchestra and the Philharmonic Orchestra Budejovice.\n\nChristoph Crois\u00e9 has been invited to perform at festivals including the Festival \"Musical Olympus\" in St. Petersburg, New York, and Baku, the [[Lucerne Festival]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.lucernefestival.ch/en/program/directory-of-artists/christoph_croise/1296 | title=Lucerne Festival &#124; Christoph Crois\u00e9}}</ref> the Davos Festival \"Young Artists in Concert\",<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nzz.ch/feuilleton/buehne/von-unerwarteten-gluecksmomenten-1.18129730 |title = Von unerwarteten Gl\u00fccksmomenten &#124; NZZ|newspaper = Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung|date = 8 August 2013|last1 = Zimmerlin|first1 = Alfred}}</ref> the [[Menuhin Festival Gstaad]], the [[Salzkammergut Festwochen Gmunden]], the [[Festival de Radio France et Montpellier|Radio France Festival Montpellier]], the Schwarzwald Music Festival, the Festival de Sully, the [[Belfast International Arts Festival]], the Emilia-Romagna Festival and the Festival de Musique de [[Wissembourg]]. As a chamber musician, he has performed with [[Dmitri Sitkovetsky]], [[Mayuko Kamio]], [[Isabelle van Keulen]], [[:de:Andrei_Wladimirowitsch_Baranow|Andrey Baranov]], Sergey Ostrovsky, [[Kirill Troussov]], Alexander Zemtsov, Vladimir Mendelssohn, Marie Chilemme, [[Christoffer Sundqvist]], [[Anna Fedorova]], [[Bartek Niziol|Bart\u0142omiej Nizio\u0142]], [[Oliver Schnyder]], Oxana Shevchenko, [[Nikita Mndoyants]], Lorenzo Soul\u00e8s, and Alexander Panfilov.\n\nSeveral of his concerts have been broadcast live on radio and television by the Bavarian Radio, the [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|Norddeutsche Rundfunk]], the [[WQXR-FM|WQXR]], the [[BBC Radio 3|BBC 3]], the [[SRF zwei|SRF]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.srf.ch/sendungen/concerto/spaetromantische-zauberei-christophe-croise-spielt-schoeck | title=Sp\u00e4tromantische Zauberei: Christophe Crois\u00e9 spielt Schoeck| year=2018}}</ref> the [[RTS2|RTS]], the [[RSI La 2|RSI]], the [[WMFT]] and others.\n\n== Instrument ==\n\nChristoph Crois\u00e9 plays on a [[Matteo Goffriller|Goffriller]] cello made in [[Venice]] in 1712.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* 2009: 1st Prize International Competition \"Petar Konjovic\", Belgrade\n* 2010: 1st Prize [[IBLA International Competition|International Competition \"IBLA Grand Prize\"]], Sicily, Italy\n* 2015: 1st Prize [[International Johannes Brahms Competition]], cello section\n* 2015: Stipendiary at the Migros Kulturprozent Competition\n* 2016: 3rd Prize International Competition \"Debut at the Berlin Philharmonic Hall\"\n* 2016: 1st Prize International Manhattan Music Competition\n* 2016: 1st Prize [[Schoenfeld International String Competition]], Harbin, China.<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://www.thestrad.com/christoph-croise-wins-alice-eleonore-international-string-competition-cello-section/ |title= Christoph Crois\u00e9 wins Alice & Eleonore Schoenfeld International String Competition cello section |date= 2016-07-31 |newspaper= The Strad |language=en-GB |access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n* 2016: 3rd Prize International [[Carlos Prieto (cellist)|Carlos Prieto]] Competition, [[Morelia]], Mexico<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://theviolinchannel.com/carlos-prieto-international-cello-competition-2016-prizes/ |title= Prizes Awarded at Mexico's Carlos Prieto International Cello Competition |newspaper= The Violin Channel |date= 2016-08-14 |language=en-US |access-date=2016-12-15 }}</ref>\n* 2016: 1st Prize Salieri-Zinetti Competition, [[Verona]], Italy.<ref>[https://theviolinchannel.com/salieri-zinetti-chamber-music-competition-prizes-verona/ 1st Prize] [http://www.salieri-zinetticompetition.eu/Salieri-Zinetti_Chamber_Music_Competition.html International Salieri-Zinetti Competition], [[Verona]], Italy</ref> \n* 2016: Stipendiary at the Migros Kulturprozent Competition and included in the Concert Agency of the [[Migros Kulturprozent]]<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://www.migros-kulturprozent.ch/de/medien/172-800-franken-fuer-den-schweizer-instrumentalmusik-nachwuchs |title= 172'800 Franken f\u00fcr den Schweizer Instrumentalmusik-Nachwuchs |publisher= Migros-Kulturprozent |access-date= 2016-12-15 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161220134735/http://www.migros-kulturprozent.ch/de/medien/172-800-franken-fuer-den-schweizer-instrumentalmusik-nachwuchs |archive-date= 20 December 2016 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n* 2017: Golden Medal \"First Berliner International Music Competition\"<ref>[http://www.berlinercompetition.com/copy-of-prior-winners Winners] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526220950/http://www.berlinercompetition.com/copy-of-prior-winners |date=26 May 2017 }}, Berliner International Music Competition</ref>\n* 2017: Swiss Ambassadors Award<ref>[https://www.eda.admin.ch/countries/united-kingdom/en/home/news/news.html/content/countries/united-kingdom/en/meta/news/2017/may/swaac Swiss Ambassadors Award], www.eda.admin.ch</ref>\n*2018: First Grand Prize \"2nd Berliner Internation